we are broken but that we are tender, perceptive, and intelligent. Thinkers such as Audre Lorde, María Lugones, Miguel de Unamuno, C. S. Lewis, Gloria Anzaldúa, and Søren Kierkegaard sat in their anger, sadness, and anxiety until their eyes adjusted to the dark. Alessandri explains how readers can cultivate “night vision” and discover new sides to their painful moods, such as wit and humor, closeness and warmth, and connection and clarity.Night Vision shows how, when we learn to embrace the dark, we begin to see these moods—and ourselves—as honorable, dignified, and unmistakably human.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aAdage.  aAdult.  aAmerican poetry.  aAndrew Solomon.  aAnger.  aAnxiety.  aAsher Brown Durand.  aBehavior.  aBipolar disorder.  aBullying.  aClergy.  aCoatlicue.  aCognitive behavioral therapy.  aCondolences.  aConsumerism.  aCredibility.  aDuke University Press.  aEmoticon.  aEpicurus.  aEthos.  aExaltation (astrology).  aExistentialism.  aFeeling.  aFireplace.  aGood and evil.  aGood cop/bad cop.  aGrief.  aHoward Thurman.  aHypoglycemia.  aImbecile.  aImpostor syndrome.  aIncest.  aIrritation.  aLaziness.  aMental disorder.  aMexican Americans.  aMood (psychology).  aMotivation.  aMourning and Melancholia.  aNational Women's Rights Convention.  aNeurasthenia.  aOf Modern Poetry.  aPain.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophy.  aPity.  aPleasure.  aPodcast.  aPoet.  aPoetry.  aPrinceton University.  aProse.  aProtest.  aPsychiatry.  aPsychologist.  aReprieve (organisation).  aRhyme.  aSadness.  aShame.  aSign language.  aSocial disruption.  aStoicism.  aSupport group.  aSøren Kierkegaard.  aThanatopsis.  aThe Norton Anthology of American Literature.  a